[University of Hawaii at Manoa|University of Hawaii, Manoa]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n|website       = {{url|hanabusa.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Colleen Wakako Hanabusa'''|\u82b1\u623f\u30b3\u30ea\u30fc\u30f3\u82e5\u5b50|Hanabusa Kor\u012bn Wakako|extra=born May 4, 1951|lead=yes}} is an [[United States|American]] politician who served as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|HI|1}} from January 2011 to January 2015. She is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].  Before her election to the U.S. House of Representatives, Hanabusa was a member of the [[Hawaii Senate]], representing the 21st District beginning in 1998.<ref name=\"Hill\">{{cite news |title=Dems pick up Hawaii seat |first=Emily |last=Goodin |newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=November 3, 2010 |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/127401-dems-pick-up-hawaii-seat |access-date=October 27, 2013}}</ref> She served as the Senate Majority Leader before being elected Hawaii's first woman President of the Senate in 2007.<ref name=emilyslist>{{citation | author=EMILY's List | work=emilyslist.org | title = Colleen Hanabusa | year=2013 | url=http://emilyslist.org/what/candidates/colleen-hanabusa | access-date=October 27, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"hanabusa2010\">{{Citation\n  | title = About Colleen\n  | work = Hanbusa for Hawaii\n  | year = 2013\n  | url = http://hanabusaforhawaii.com/about-colleen/\n  | access-date = October 27, 2013}}</ref> On August 24, 2011, she announced her intention to run for reelection to Congress.<ref name=\"HCB 2012 re-run\">{{citation | last=Blair | first=Chad | title=No Senate Run for Hanabusa | date=August 24, 2011 | work=Honolulu Civil Beat | publisher=Peer News | url=http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2011/08/24/12630-no-senate-run-for-hanabusa/ | access-date=August 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, 2012, after the death of Senator [[Daniel Inouye]] of Hawaii, it was announced that Inouye had sent a letter shortly before his death to the [[Governor of Hawaii]], [[Neil Abercrombie]], stating his desire that Hanabusa be appointed to his seat. Abercrombie decided against appointing Hanabusa and chose [[Lieutenant Governor of Hawaii]] [[Brian Schatz]] instead.<ref name=\"politico.com\">{{citation| last= Isenstadt | first=Alex | title=Colleen Hanabusa favorite for Daniel Inouye seat | date=December 17, 2012 | work=Politico.com | url=http://www.politico.com/story/2012/12/hanabusa-seen-as-favorite-for-inouye-seat-85207.html | access-date=October 27, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN.com\">{{citation | url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2012/12/18/inouye-gave-preference-for-successor-before-he-died/ |title=Inouye gave preference for successor before he died | work=CNN PoliticalTicker | date=December 18, 2012 |access-date=October 27, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{citation | last=Glueck | first=Katie | title=Brian Schatz chosen to replace Daniel Inouye | date=December 27, 2012 | work=Politico.com | url=http://www.politico.com/story/2012/12/report-replacing-inouye-down-to-3-85509.html | access-date=October 27, 2013}}</ref> Hanabusa announced a Democratic primary challenge to the incumbent Schatz in the 2014 special election, but lost the close primary contest.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cheney |first=Kyle |last2=Dovere |first2=Edward-Isaac |date=August 16, 2014 |title=Brian Schatz edges Colleen Hanabusa in Hawaii primary |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/08/hawaii-election-results-2014-brian-schatz-colleen-hanabusa-110074.html |newspaper=Politico |access-date=November 22, 2014 }}</ref> Hanabusa announced her intention to run in the [[Hawaii's 1st congressional district special election, 2016|1st congressional district special election]] to fill the remaining term of Rep. [[Mark Takai]], and won the Democratic primary for the race on August 13, 2016.<ref>[http://www.rafu.com/2016/08/schatz-hanabusa-gabbard-win-hawaii-democratic-primaries/]</ref> Hanabusa also won the election on November 8, 2016 and was sworn in on November 14.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/three-house-lawmakers-sworn-in-just-before-congress-ends/article/2607385 |title=Three House lawmakers sworn in just before Congress ends |last=Duran |first=Nicole |date=November 14, 2016 |website=Washington Examiner}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nA fourth-generation [[Japanese American|American of Japanese ancestry]], Colleen Hanabusa grew up in [[Wai'anae, Hawai'i|Wai{{okina}}anae]] with her two younger brothers, her parents, and her grandparents. In 1969 she graduated from [[Saint Andrew's Priory School for Girls|St. Andrew's Priory]]. She received a B.A. in economics and sociology in 1973 and an M.A. in sociology in 1975 from the [[University of Hawai'i]] and in 1977 received a J.D. from the University of Hawai'i's [[William S. Richardson School of Law]].<ref name=\"HW Rees\">{{citation | last = Rees | first = Robert M. | title = Queen of the Senate | newspaper=[[Honolulu Weekly]] | date = June 12, 2002 | url=http://www.honoluluweekly.com/archives/coverstory%20%202002/06-12-02%20Hanabusa/06-12-02%20Hanabusa.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927085027/http://www.honoluluweekly.com/archives/coverstory%20%202002/06-12-02%20Hanabusa/06-12-02%20Hanabusa.html | archive-date=September 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Law career==\nHanabusa is a labor lawyer with almost 30 years of experience, and a corporate officer in a family-run corporation. She has been recognized in The Best Lawyers in America, Woodward and White, Inc., served as a delegate to the Hawai`i State Judicial Conference, and was noted in ''[[Honolulu Magazine]]'' as one of Hawai`i's A+ Attorneys in 1993 and subsequent years.\n\n==Hawaii Senate==\nIn November 1998, Hanabusa was elected as the [[Hawaii Senate|state senator]] from the 21st District. The 21st District includes [[Wai'anae, Hawaii|Wai'anae]], where her family has resided for four generations, as well as [[Ko Olina Resort|Ko Olina]], [[Kahe Point]], [[Nanakuli, Hawaii|Nanakuli]], [[M\u0101'ili, Hawai'i|Ma'ili]], [[Makaha, Hawaii|Makaha]], [[Makua, Hawaii|Makua]] and [[Kaena Point|Ka'ena Point]].\n\nOne of Hanabusa's first acts upon being elected was to organize senators to vote against the second-term confirmation of [[Attorney General of Hawaii|Hawaii Attorney General]] [[Margery Bronster]].<ref name=\"HW Rees\" />\n\nHanabusa served as Senate Majority Leader before being elected the first woman President of the Senate in 2006&nbsp;\u2013 making her the first Asian American woman to preside over a state legislative chamber in the United States.<ref name=\"emilyslist\"/> In 2003 she was named one of Hawaii\u2019s \u201ctop ten political power brokers\u201d, along with the state\u2019s governor and two U.S. senators, by ''[[Hawaii Business Magazine]].''<ref name=businessmagazine>{{citation | title = Hawaii\u2019s Powerbrokers (List) | newspaper=Honolulu Business Magazine | date = October 2003 | url=http://www.hawaiibusiness.com/Hawaii-Business/October-2003/Hawaiias-Powerbrokers-List/|access-date=May 14, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHanabusa previously ran unsuccessfully in a special election held in January 2003 to replace the late [[Patsy T. Mink]] as U.S. Representative from [[Hawaii's 2nd congressional district|Hawai'i's 2nd congressional district]], losing to [[Ed Case]], a [[Blue Dog Coalition|Blue Dog]] Democrat.<ref>{{citation| last=Gima| first=Craig| title=Victorious Case sees end of old-style politics| date=January 6, 2003| newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin| url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2003/01/06/news/index1.html| access-date=January 7, 2011}}</ref> In 2006 she ran for the same seat after Case retired to unsuccessfully challenge Senator [[Daniel Akaka]] in the Democratic primary. Hanabusa was again unsuccessful, losing in the Democratic primary to former [[Lieutenant Governor of Hawaii|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Mazie Hirono]] by 844 votes.<ref>{{citation| last=Reyes| first=B.J.| title=Statewide name recognition gives Hirono the advantage| date=September 25, 2006| newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin| url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2006/09/25/news/story03.html| access-date=January 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Leadership positions===\n*Serving the Leeward Coast as State Senator since 1998\n*State Senate President since 2007\n*State Senate Majority Leader since 2007\n*Chair, Judiciary and Hawaiian Affairs Committee\n*Co-chair, Joint Senate House Task Force on Ice and Drug Abatement\n*Senate's first statewide hearings on Rice v. Cayetano\n*United States Supreme Court decision Co-Chair, Joint Senate House Investigative Committee: Felix Consent Decree\n*2001 Vice Chair, Senate Ways and Means Committee\n*Vice President, State Senate\n*Chair, Senate Committee on Water, Land, and Hawaiian Affairs<ref name=\"hanabusa2010\" />\n\n===Key legislation introduced===\n*3 R's program for repair and maintenance of schools\n*Repeal of the Van Cam Law\n*Tax credit to enable construction and jobs at Ko Olina\n*Bill to reform election contributions\n*Bill to pay the awards of the Individual Rights Panel-DHHL\n*Bill to require community notice prior to establishing a halfway house\n*Bill for a ceded land inventory Education Initiatives<ref name=\"hanabusa2010\" />\n\n===Controversies===\nIn 2002, when in the State Legislature, Hanabusa emerged as the leading advocate for legislation authorizing $75 million in tax credits for [[Ko Olina Resort]], a move she declared necessary to spur development for the Leeward area, but which others saw as a reward for a close associate and political backer, Ko Olina developer Jeff Stone. When Governor [[Ben Cayetano]] vetoed the tax credit bill, Hanabusa took the unprecedented step of suing to overturn the veto.<ref name=KoOlina>{{citation| last=Pang | first=Gordon Y.K. | title = Is 2nd time charm for U.S. House candidate? |newspaper=[[Honolulu Advertiser]] | date=August 29, 2006 | url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2006/Aug/29/ln/FP608290346.html/|access-date=May 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation| title=Senator sees no conflict in many ties to Ko Olina | first=Jim | last=Dooley | newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser | date=March 4, 2004 | url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2004/Mar/04/ln/ln03a.html | access-date=June 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWithin months, Hanabusa's then-fianc\u00e9 John Souza received a preferential deal in purchasing one of Stone's homes in Ko Olina. In February 2005, less than two years after Souza bought the home, he sold it for a $421,000 profit, according to real estate records. Souza and Hanabusa, who were engaged at the time and married in 2008, then bought a $1-million home in another Ko Olina subdivision developed by Centex Homes of Texas.<ref>{{citation| last=Dooley | first=Jim | title=Exclusive Report: Close Ties Between Congressional Candidate Colleen Hanabusa and Ko Olina Developer Rake in Funds | newspaper=Hawaii Reporter | date=October 28, 2010 | url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/exclusive-report-close-ties-between-congressional-candidate-colleen-hanabusa-and-koolina-developer-rake-in-funds | access-date=February 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Ko Olina tax-credit legislation, intended to promote development of a \u201cworld-class\u201d aquarium at the resort, expired after plans for the aquarium were abandoned. Ko Olina Resort eventually returned the tax credit, but the [[Linda Lingle|Lingle]] Administration and Hanabusa disagreed on how to use the returned funds.<ref name=KoOlina2>{{citation| last=Kua | first=Crystal | title = Ko Olina Resort returns tax credit of $75 million | newspaper=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]] | volume=12 | issue=18 | date= January 18, 2007 | url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2007/01/18/news/story01.html | access-date=May 14, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWhile in Congress, Hanabusa was called a \"loan shark\" by the Center for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington for abusing her position to pay herself excessive interest payments to settling her campaign debt. Hanabusa's spokesperson stated these interest payments were merely repayment of a bank loan.<ref>{{citation| last=Dooley | first=Jim | title=Hanabusa Rips Washington Group Calling Her A \"Loan Shark\" | newspaper=Hawaii Reporter | date=March 22, 2012 | url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/hanabusa-rips-washington-group-calling-her-a-loan-shark/123 | access-date=March 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Hanabusa appeared on ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'', where she criticized a derogatory comment O'Reilly made toward Asians. O'Reilly condemned her for not watching the very program in which he made his statement, even though his comment was still widely considered as offensive. O'Reilly had previously commented on various social issues in Hawaii.<ref>{{citation| title=Hanabusa, O'Reilly tangle over report | newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser | date=January 12, 2013 | url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/newspremium/20130112_Hanabusa_OReilly_tangle_over_report.html?id=186588151| access-date=February 1, 2013}} {{subscriptionrequired}}</ref>\n\nWhen State Rep. Glenn Wakai introduced legislation to prevent the eating of dogs and cats, Hanabusa refused to hold hearings on it in the State Senate Judiciary Committee, preventing it from passing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/03/05/news/briefs.html |title=Honolulu Star-Bulletin News /2005/03/05/ |publisher=Archives.starbulletin.com |date= |access-date=August 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n[[File:Colleen Hanabusa - Aloha Floral Parade 2010.jpg|thumb|right|Hanabusa at the Aloha Floral Parade in 2010]]\n\n====2010====\n\n{{Main article|Hawaii's 1st congressional district special election, 2010|United States House of Representatives elections in Hawaii, 2010#District 1}}\n\nHanabusa ran unsuccessfully in the May 22, 2010, special election to serve out the remaining months of former Representative [[Neil Abercrombie]]'s term; then-City Councilman [[Charles Djou]] was able to defeat her without winning a majority of the votes under the rules of the winner-take-all election that split the Democratic vote between Hanabusa and rival [[Ed Case]], a moderate Democrat.<ref name=depledge>{{Citation\n  | last = DePledge\n  | first = Derrick\n  | title = Hawaii candidates for Congress outline policy differences\n  | newspaper = [[Honolulu Advertiser]]\n  | date = January 14, 2010\n  | url = http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/Jan/14/ln/hawaii1140326.html\n  | access-date = March 5, 2011}}</ref><ref name=Djou>{{Citation\n  | last=DePledge\n  | first=Derrick\n  | title = Election results show Djou's appeal outside East Honolulu\n  | date = May 24, 2010\n  | url = http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/May/24/ln/hawaii5240346.html\n  | newspaper = Honolulu Advertiser\n  | access-date = January 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nU.S. Senators [[Daniel Inouye]] and [[Daniel Akaka]] supported Hanabusa's special election campaign and backed her again in the September Democratic primary. Some in the national [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] indicated a preference for Case, who previously served in the U.S. House of Representatives before an unsuccessful U.S. Senate primary challenge to Akaka in 2006. The national Democratic leadership remained officially neutral.<ref>{{citation| last=DePledge| first=Derrick| title=Hanabusa defies polls, will stay in race| date=May 6, 2010| newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser| url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/May/06/ln/hawaii5060342.html| access-date=January 7, 2011}}</ref><ref name=depledge2>{{Citation\n  | last = DePledge\n  | first = Derrick\n  | title = Senators boost Hanabusa\n  | newspaper = Honolulu Advertiser\n  | date = January 10, 2010\n  | url = http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/Jan/10/ln/hawaii1100359.html\n  | access-date = March 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn May 30, 2010, Case, citing his third-place showing in the special election and to avoid a rift among Democrats that could lead to Djou's winning the November election, announced his withdrawal from the race and gave his support to Hanabusa.<ref>{{citation| last=DePledge | first=Derrick | title=Case stuns with withdrawal from Hawaii congressional primary | date=May 31, 2010 | newspaper=Honolulu Advertiser | url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/May/31/ln/hawaii5310345.html | access-date=February 7, 2011}}</ref> That placed Hanabusa as the top Democratic candidate in the September party primary, which she then won.<ref>{{citation| author=Star-Advertiser staff | title=Djou and Hanabusa have rematch Nov. 2 | date=September 19, 2010 | newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser | url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/elections/2010/primary/20100919_Djou_and_Hanabusa_have_rematch_Nov_2.html | access-date=February 7, 2011}}</ref> Hanabusa subsequently challenged Djou for the same seat and on November 2 won the general election by a 53.2% to 46.8% margin.<ref name=\"Hill\"/><ref>{{citation| url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/results/house | title=House Map \u2013 Election Results 2010 \u2013 The New York Times | newspaper=New York Times | access-date=February 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation| last=Reyes | first=B.J. | title=Hanabusa sweeps districts | date=November 4, 2010 | newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser | url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20101104_Hanabusa_sweeps_districts.html | access-date=February 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====2012====\n{{Main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Hawaii, 2012#District 1}}\n\nAlthough there was some speculation that she would run to succeed retiring Senator [[Daniel Akaka]], Hanabusa opted to run for reelection to Congress.<ref name=\"HCB 2012 re-run\" />  She faced Djou again, and defeated him with 54.6 percent of the vote.\n\n====2016====\n{{Main article|Hawaii's 1st congressional district special election, 2016|United States House of Representatives elections in Hawaii, 2016}}\n\nIn May 2016, Hanabusa's successor in the House, [[Mark Takai]], announced he was not running for reelection that year due to [[pancreatic cancer]]. Hanabusa subsequently announced that she would once again run for the seat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/breaking-news/hanabusa-to-run-for-u-s-house-to-succeed-takai/|title=Hanabusa to run for U.S. House to succeed Takai|first=Kevin|last=Dayton|work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|date=May 25, 2016}}</ref> Prior to his July 20, 2016 death, Takai had endorsed Hanabusa to succeed him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32093411/takai-endorses-hanabusa|title=Takai endorses Hanabusa in congressional race|last=Daysog|first=Rick|work=Hawaii News Now|date=May 29, 2016}}</ref> Two weeks after his death, on August 3, Hanabusa announced that she would also run in the [[special election]] that is set for November 8, 2016, the same date as the regularly-scheduled election, to finish Takai's term in the [[114th United States Congress]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Dayton|first=Kevin|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/hawaii-news/special-election-winner-will-finish-takais-term/|title=Special-election winner will finish Takai\u2019s term|work=[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]]|date=August 3, 2016|access-date=August 5, 2016}}</ref> On August 13, she easily won the Democratic primary for the general election.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cole|first=William|title=Schatz, Hanabusa, Gabbard cruise to victory in congressional races|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/breaking-news/hanabusa-schatz-rack-up-early-leads-in-house-senate-races/|work=[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]]|date=August 13, 2016|access-date=August 15, 2016}}</ref> On October 24, Hanabusa officially resigned from Chairman of the [[Honolulu Rail Transit|HART]] Board, seeking reelection to the [[United States House of Representatives]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Honor\u00e9|first=Marcel|title=Longtime construction executive to replace Hanabusa on HART board|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/10/28/breaking-news/longtime-construction-executive-to-replace-hanabusa-on-hart-board/|work=[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]]|date=October 28, 2016|access-date=November 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nAfter House GOP leader [[John Boehner]] (R-OH) pledged to give incumbent Congressman Charles Djou a seat on the Appropriations Committee, Senator [[Daniel Inouye]] (D-HI) stated that Democrats would also name Hanabusa to Appropriations.<ref>{{citation| title=Inouye: Hanabusa would win appropriations spot | date=October 20, 2010 | newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser | author=Associated Press | url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/breaking/105359163.html | access-date=February 7, 2011}}</ref>  However, House Democratic leadership instead appointed her to the Armed Services and Natural Resources committees.<ref>{{citation| author=Associated Press | title=Hanabusa appointed to armed services and natural resources committees | date=January 19, 2011 | newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser | url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/breaking/114242329.html | access-date=February 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHanabusa was the third [[Buddhist]] to join the United States Congress, the previous ones being [[Hank Johnson]] of Georgia and [[Mazie Hirono]] of Hawaii.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pewforum.org/2015/01/05/faith-on-the-hill/2/ |title=Faith on the Hill: The Religious Composition of the 114th Congress |date=January 5, 2015 |access-date=September 13, 2016 |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |quote=The number of Buddhists in Congress fell from three to two, as Rep. Colleen Hanabusa, D-Hawaii, lost her bid for a Senate seat. }}</ref> Hanabusa's election makes Hawaii the only state with a majority non-Christian House delegation.  She is a member of the [[New Democrat Coalition]].\n\n===Legislation===\nAs a Representative, Hanabusa has sponsored 14 bills, including:<ref>{{cite web|title=Representative Hanabusa's Legislation|url=http://www.congress.gov/member/colleen-hanabusa/2010?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22Hanabusa%22%5D%2C%22sponsorship%22%3A%22sponsored%22%2C%22type%22%3A%22bills%22%7D|publisher=Library of Congress|access-date=December 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====112th Congress (2011-2012)====\n* H.R. 3320, a bill to increase funds for grants to U.S. owned Pacific islands to offset costs resulting from the residency of people from a [[Compact of Free Association]] (COFA) member-state, introduced November 2, 2011. Hanabusa introduced a similar bill, H.R. 1222, in the 113th Congress.\n\n====113th Congress (2013-2014)====\n* H.R. 912, a bill to allow for [[Medicaid]] to provide care to people lawfully residing in a U.S. owned Pacific island who are from a COFA member-state, introduced February 28, 2013\n* H.R. 2225, a bill to change [[Memorial Day]] from the last Monday in May to its previous date of May 30, introduced June 3, 2013\n\nIn addition to the bills listed above, Hanabusa has sponsored several bills relating to Filipino World War II veterans that would, among other things, recognize their efforts in [[World War II]] and provide veteran benefits to them.\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces]]\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Readiness|Subcommittee on Readiness]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n**[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Indian and Alaska Native Affairs|Subcommittee on Indian and Alaska Native Affairs]] (Ranking Member)\n**[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Public Lands and Environmental Regulation|Subcommittee on Public Lands and Environmental Regulation]]\n**[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources|Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources]]\n\n==2014 U.S. Senate election==\n{{See also|United States Senate special election in Hawaii, 2014 }}\nOn December 17, 2012, the [[List of members of the United States Congress by longevity of service|second-longest serving U.S. Senator in history]], [[Daniel Inouye]], who had represented the state of Hawaii since it became a state in 1959, died of respiratory complications.<ref>{{citation| last1=Elving | first1=Ron | last2=Block | first2=Melissa | title=Hawaii Sen. Daniel Inouye Dies At 88 Of Respiratory Complications | date=December 17, 2012 | work=NPR.org | url=http://www.npr.org/2012/12/17/167484210/hawaii-sen-daniel-inouye-dies-at-88-of-respiratory-complications | access-date=October 27, 2013}}</ref> Shortly before his passing, Inouye sent a letter to Hawaii Governor [[Neil Abercrombie]] requesting that Hanabusa be appointed to his seat for the remainder of his term. Hanabusa submitted her name for consideration to the [[Democratic Party of Hawaii]],<ref>{{citation| last=Wong | first=Scott | title=Hanabusa to apply for Inouye's Hawaii Senate seat | date=December 19, 2012 | work=Politico.com | url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/on-congress/2012/12/hanabusa-to-apply-for-inouyes-hawaii-senate-seat-152474.html | access-date=October 27, 2013}}</ref> which then included her on a list of three candidates for Abercrombie's consideration.<ref name=\"politico.com\"/><ref name=\"CNN.com\"/><ref>{{citation | last1=DePledge | first1=Derrick | last2=Reyes | first2=B.J. | title=Mr. Schatz goes to Washington | date=December 27, 2012 | newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser | url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/newspremium/20121227__Mr_Schatz_goes_to_Washington.html | access-date=October 27, 2013}} {{subscriptionrequired}}</ref> Abercrombie then chose to appoint [[Lieutenant Governor of Hawaii]] [[Brian Schatz]] to the seat.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>{{citation| last=Blair | first=Chad | title=Why Abercrombie Didn't Pick Hanabusa  | date=December 26, 2012 | work=Honolulu Civil Beat | publisher=Peer News | url=http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2012/12/26/17981-why-abercrombie-didnt-pick-hanabusa/ | access-date=October 27, 2013}}</ref> On December 26, 2012 Schatz was sworn in by [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Joe Biden]]. On May 2, 2013, Hanabusa announced she would challenge Schatz in the 2014 Democratic primary. She said \"Brian was not elected. He was appointed, and I don't think the people have really had an opportunity to weigh in on who they want to represent them in the United States Senate.\"<ref>{{citation| last=Garcia | first=Oskar | title=Hanabusa announces US Senate run in Hawaii | date=May 2, 2013 | work=Yahoo News | agency=Associated Press | url=http://news.yahoo.com/hanabusa-announces-us-senate-run-hawaii-214647549.html | access-date=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May, Inouye's widow, Irene, endorsed Hanabusa saying \u201cShortly after she was elected president of the Hawaii State Senate, Dan recognized that Colleen was more than capable of succeeding him and he began to mentor her. His last wish was that Colleen serve out his term because he was confident in her ability to step into the Senate and immediately help Hawaii.\"<ref name=\"Politco Widow\">{{citation| last=Schultheis | first= Emily | title=Daniel Inouye's widow endorses Colleen Hanabusa over Brian Schatz | date=May 3, 2013 | work=Politico.com | url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/05/inouyes-widow-endorses-hanabusa-over-schatz-90892.html | access-date=October 27, 2013}}</ref> Hanabusa's campaign hired many of Inouye's staffers.<ref>{{citation| last1=Blair | first1=Chad | last2=Grube | first2=Nick | title=Can Inouye's Ghost Take Down Sen. Brian Schatz? | date=June 24, 2013 | work=Honolulu Civil Beat | publisher=Peer News | url=http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2013/06/24/19374-can-dan-inouyes-ghost-take-down-senator-brian-schatz/ | access-date=October 27, 2013}}</ref> Polling throughout the campaign was controversially mixed, with each campaign releasing different poll results.<ref>{{citation| last=Burns | first=Alexander | title=Hawaii Dems clash on 2014 polls | date=July 3, 2013 | work=Politico.com | url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/07/colleen-hanabusa-hawaii-senate-democratic-primary-2014-poll-93657.html | access-date=October 27, 2013}}</ref>  In the end, Schatz won a narrow victory (115,401 to 113,632).\n\n==Inter-Congressional career==\nAfter leaving Congress, Hanabusa has continued with her labor law practice. In June 2015, Hanabusa was appointed by Honolulu mayor [[Kirk Caldwell]] to the board of directors of the Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation (HART), the operator of [[Honolulu Rail Transit]],<ref>[http://www.civilbeat.com/2015/06/hanabusa-picked-to-help-monitor-honolulu-rail-project/]</ref> to replace Carrie Okinaga. She also serves on the board of directors for Hawaii Gas.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2015/06/04/hawaii-gas-names-hanabusa-matsumoto-ngo-to-board.html| title = Hawaii Gas names Colleen Hanabusa, Colbert Matsumoto, Catherine Ngo to board of directors \u2013 Pacific Business News| website = Pacific Business News| access-date = February 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Colleen Hanabusa}}\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Hawaii/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Colleen_Hanabusa_%5BD-1%5D}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = H001050 | ballot = Colleen_Hanabusa | nndb = 536/000264741 | votesmart = 17745 | govtrack = 412418 | opencong = 412418 | rollcall = 17283 | politifact = | fec = H2HI02110 | opensecrets = N00025881 | followthemoney = 3356 | assets = colleen-hanabusa | legistorm = 2746/Rep_Colleen_Hanabusa_HI.html | ontheissues = House/Colleen_Hanabusa.htm | congress = colleen-hanabusa/2010 | worldcat = np-hanabusa,%20colleen | c-span = colleenwakakohanabusa | imdb = | bloom